The CAO may disqualify a person from acting as an AR for up to one year if the CAO has evidence that the AR has:

Misrepresented a household’s circumstances;

Knowingly provided false information about the household ; or

Made improper use of benefits.

NOTE: The CAO must not disqualify a group living arrangement (GLA) or a drug or alcohol treatment center acting as an AR for its residents.

The CAO must send an Advance Notice of Adverse Action to the household and to the AR 30 days before the disqualification date. The notice must include:

The proposed action;

The reason for the proposed action;

The household’s right to ask for a fair hearing;

The telephone number of the CAO; and

The name of the person to contact for more information (if possible).

7 CFR 273.2(n)(4)(i)(C)

Updated May 8, 2024, replacing March 1, 2012

Residents of GLA s who receive disability benefits such as SSI or RSDI, VA or railroad retirement and who are blind or disabled may be eligible for SNAP benefits as a separate household from others with whom they live.

7 CFR § 273.1(b)(7)(vi)

This includes residents who:

receive SSI or RSDI because of blindness or disability;

receive SSI or RSDI because of age and are blind or disabled (as proven by a doctor’s statement);

receive VA disability benefits;

have a permanent disability and are a veteran’s surviving spouse or child entitled to non-service-connected death benefits;

receive a Railroad Retirement annuity and have applied for disability benefits.

receive Medicaid benefits in a disability category where the disability has been certified by Social Security or the Medical Review Team. Disability cannot be presumptive.

7 CFR § 271.2 “Elderly or disabled member”

GLA residents who are not blind or disabled recipients receiving aged or disability benefits listed in this section are not eligible for SNAP. They are not considered household members if they live with an eligible GLA resident.

The gaining CAO will take the following actions when notified of the intercounty transfer:

Enter the case into Application Processing;

Open all budget group members for the remainder of the certification period. (There must be no lapse in benefits.);

Review ABAWD status, if applicable;.

Determine through system inquiry the date the transfer will be effective;

Request the transfer of case file material;

Narrate receipt of the case and any relevant information relating to the transfer; and

Ensure that duplicate participation does not occur.

NOTE: Expedited service procedures do not apply in an intercounty transfer, as there is no break in the household’s receipt of benefits.

NOTE: Any appeal will be heard in the new county of residence.

The CAO will:

p rovide PA 772 at certification and renewal for all nonexempt work registrants (see Chapter 535.3 )

fully inform each SNAP applicant and recipient of the services offered by participation in SNAP E&T at interview and renewal;

encourage individuals to volunteer for SNAP E&T by describing the E&T contracted programs available in the area (see: Appendix B ) and the services they offer, including education, training, SPALs, placement, and retention services designed to assist the individual and their family to become economically secure;

code each household member with an appropriate ETP Status Code;

review formal requests from a contracted program to enroll participants who directly reached out to the contracted program, otherwise known as “reverse referrals”, within 15 calendar days of receipt; these requests are submitted using the Reverse Referral Form, PA 1951;

assist with the completion of the EDP (PA 1531) when an individual volunteers to participate in an allowable SNAP E&T activity;

update the PA 1531 at renewal or when there is a change in participation status; the EDP does not have to be updated solely to issue a SPAL.

7 CFR § 273.7(c)(1)

Updated July 8, 2021, replacing May 19, 2021

Effective September 1, 2024 :

Discretionary exemptions will be used to exempt the following;

Exempting the following ABAWDs who meet state employment and training exemption criteria:

Full-time VISTA Volunteer (Title I DVSA) (ETP Status 06)

Expected to return to work within 60 days (ETP Status 15)

Travel time is two or more hours round-trip from an employment/education training site (ETP Status 19)

Receiving expedited SNAP only and meets no exemption code (ETP Status 23)

For June 1, 2025 – September 30,2025 , exempting all ABAWDs until renewal but no later than October 1, 2025 (for current recipients) who are not eligible for any other exemption and who are not meeting the work requirement in:

Adams County;

Centre County;

Chester County;

Lancaster County excluding the City of Lancaster;

Lebanon County excluding the City of Lebanon;

Montgomery County excluding the Municipality of Norristown;

York County excluding the City of York, York Township, and Springettsbury Township

Municipalities – Cranberry Township (Butler County), and Hampden Township (Cumberland County)

For September 2025 only, exempting all ABAWDs who are not eligible for any other exemption, who are not meeting the work requirement, and who:

Were receiving SNAP in a waived area as of August 22, 2025; and

are between the ages of 44 – 54, regardless of county of residence

NOTE: Individuals who meet these temporary additional criteria will be assigned SNAP ETP Code 27 and SNAP Qual Code 9 by Headquarters and will not be subject to the time limit for the specified temporary period . Headquarters will report the number of discretionary exemptions used to exempt these individuals to the USDA Food and Nutrition Service (FNS).

Updated September 3, 2025; Replacing September 30, 2024

The CAO will not count the value of a transferred resource if:

The resource was transferred more than three months before the application date;

The transferred resource plus other countable resources did not exceed the resource limit at the time of transfer ;

The sale or trade of the resource was made at or near fair market value ;

The resource was transferred between members of the same household, including ineligible noncitizens or disqualified individuals whose resources are considered available to the household; or

The resource was transferred for reasons other than to qualify for SNAP, such as funds put in an educational trust fund by a parent.

7 CFR § 273.8(h)

Allowable mortgage expenses:

Repayment of a loan to purchase a mobile home;

Repayment of a second, third, or later mortgage;

Costs for loans involving liens or judgments when failure to make the payment may result in the loss of the household’s shelter

Example: An arrested person borrowed money for bail, using his home as collateral. Payments are allowable as shelter costs, because failure to pay the loan, including interest, would result in the loss of the household’s shelter.
